    "summary": "NATO's air campaign against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, conducted from March 24 to June 10, 1999, was carried out to halt Serbian security forces' campaign of ethnic cleansing against the Albanian population of Kosovo. The bombing campaign lasted 78 days and involved aircraft from nineteen NATO member states flying over 38,000 sorties. It was NATO's first military action against a sovereign state and proceeded without explicit UN Security Council authorization, generating significant controversy about the legality and precedent of humanitarian intervention.\n\nThe campaign targeted Yugoslav military infrastructure, air defenses, bridges, factories, and communications networks. Several incidents caused civilian casualties, including the accidental bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade, which killed three Chinese journalists and provoked a severe diplomatic crisis with China. Yugoslav forces withdrew from Kosovo in June 1999 following Milošević's acceptance of a peace plan, and a NATO-led peacekeeping force (KFOR) entered the province. Kosovo was placed under UN administration. The province declared independence in 2008, recognized by many Western nations but not by Serbia, Russia, or China, leaving its status internationally contested.",
